<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12003b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12003b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12003b"> 3(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> les incises</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il y a dans les tours pr&eacute;cit&eacute;s <mark>des incises</mark> presque admises par l&apos;usage. Tels sont: <i>reconnut, insista</i>, et &agrave; la rigueur <i>ponctua</i>.&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &ldquo;Vous savez que les incises de la conversation mise en r&eacute;cit doivent &ecirc;tre essentiellement vagues et passer presque inaper&ccedil;ues. Elles se r&eacute;duisent &agrave; des esp&egrave;ces de signes de ponctuation.&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[In the above turns of phrase there are embedded clauses that are almost accepted in usage, such as: <i>reconnut, insista</i>, and even <i>ponctua</i>.&rdquo; [&hellip;]</font> &ldquo;You know that the <mark>embedded clauses</mark> in a narrated conversation must remain vague, they should hardly be noticed at all. They function almost like a sort of punctuation sign.] <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 243</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
